# payroll system

## HOW TO RUN (WINDOWS POWERSHELL)

### STEP 1 — GO TO PROJECT FOLDER

```
cd "C:\Users\heart\Downloads\PayDay" 
```

---

### STEP 2 — COMPILE TERMINAL UI

```
gcc main.c src/ui/ConsoleUI.c src/utils/CSVManager.c src/core/PayrollEngine.c -o app.exe
```

---

### STEP 3 — RUN TERMINAL UI

```
.\app.exe
```

---

### STEP 4 — COMPILE BACKEND SERVER

```
gcc server_main.c src/server/HttpServer.c src/utils/CSVManager.c src/core/PayrollEngine.c -o server.exe
```

---

### STEP 5 — RUN SERVER

```
.\server.exe
```

---

## BASIC CONCEPTS

### What is .c?

It contains how the modules work (implementation).

### What is .h?

It contains struct definitions, function declarations, and what the module offers.

### Why split?

To organize the code better and make it easier to maintain.

---

### What is a struct?

A custom data type that groups related variables together.
Without struct, too many separate variables would be needed, making the code messy.

### Why use struct arrays?

Because each row from CSV maps naturally to one struct object.
That makes the data easier to process.

### What is an enum?

A named list of constant values.

---

## DATA STORAGE

### How is data stored?

In CSV text files.

### Why CSV?

Easier to read and inspect.
Simpler than using SQL for a small project.

### What is soft delete?

Instead of removing data, it marks it as inactive.

---

## PROGRAM FLOW

### What happens when the program starts?

* Creates data folder if missing
* Ensures payroll.csv has a header
* Loads employees.csv
* Shows login screen
* Routes user to admin or employee menu

---

## CSV FUNCTIONS

### What is csv_load_employees()?

Reads employees.csv, converts each row into an Employee struct, and stores them in an array.

### What is csv_save_employees()?

Writes the employee array back into employees.csv.

### What is csv_load_payroll()?

Reads payroll.csv and converts rows into PayrollRecord structs.

### What is csv_save_payroll()?

Saves payroll records back into payroll.csv.

---

## MEMORY

### What happens after data is changed in memory?

The program saves the updated array back to CSV so changes are not lost.

---

## SYSTEM COMPONENTS

### What is the role of CSVManager?

It is the storage layer.

### What is the role of HttpServer?

It is the backend server layer.
It accepts HTTP requests and returns JSON responses.

---

## FRONTEND CONNECTION

### How does the GUI/browser connect to the backend?

* Browser sends HTTP requests
* Server receives JSON
* Processes data
* Reads/writes CSV
* Returns JSON response

---

## ENTRY POINTS

### Why does the project have main.c and server_main.c?

They are two different entry points.

* main.c → runs terminal app
* server_main.c → runs backend server

---

## DESIGN CHOICES

### Why use arrays instead of a database?

Because this is a small, lightweight project.
Arrays are simpler and enough for this use case.

### Why does the backend return JSON?

Because browser/frontend apps understand JSON easily.
It is the standard format for web APIs.
